events.description: The Second Council of Constantinople begins.
events.html: • 553 – The Second Council of Constantinople begins.[1]

events.description: Rebel barons renounce their allegiance to King John of England — part of a chain of events leading to the signing of the Magna Carta.
events.html: • 1215 – Rebel barons renounce their allegiance to King John of England — part of a chain of events leading to the signing of the Magna Carta.

events.description: Kublai Khan becomes ruler of the Mongol Empire.
events.html: • 1260 – Kublai Khan becomes ruler of the Mongol Empire.[2]

events.description: On his second voyage to the New World, Christopher Columbus sights Jamaica, landing at Discovery Bay and declares Jamaica the property of the Spanish crown.
events.html: • 1494 – On his second voyage to the New World, Christopher Columbus sights Jamaica, landing at Discovery Bay and declares Jamaica the property of the Spanish crown.[3]

events.description: Daimyō (Lord) Shimazu Tadatsune of the Satsuma Domain in southern Kyūshū, Japan, completes his successful invasion of the Ryūkyū Kingdom in Okinawa.
events.html: • 1609 – Daimyō (Lord) Shimazu Tadatsune of the Satsuma Domain in southern Kyūshū, Japan, completes his successful invasion of the Ryūkyū Kingdom in Okinawa.[4]

events.description: King Charles I of England dissolves the Short Parliament.
events.html: • 1640 – King Charles I of England dissolves the Short Parliament.[5]

events.description: Cromwell's Act of Grace, aimed at reconciliation with the Scots, proclaimed in Edinburgh.
events.html: • 1654 – Cromwell's Act of Grace, aimed at reconciliation with the Scots, proclaimed in Edinburgh.

events.description: Russia and Prussia sign the Treaty of St. Petersburg.
events.html: • 1762 – Russia and Prussia sign the Treaty of St. Petersburg.

events.description: In France, the Estates-General convenes for the first time since 1614.
events.html: • 1789 – In France, the Estates-General convenes for the first time since 1614.

events.description: Mary Kies becomes the first woman awarded a U.S. patent, for a technique of weaving straw with silk and thread.
events.html: • 1809 – Mary Kies becomes the first woman awarded a U.S. patent, for a technique of weaving straw with silk and thread.

events.description: Emperor Napoleon dies in exile on the island of Saint Helena in the South Atlantic Ocean.
events.html: • 1821 – Emperor Napoleon dies in exile on the island of Saint Helena in the South Atlantic Ocean.

events.description: The first edition of The Manchester Guardian, now The Guardian, is published.
events.html: • 1821 – The first edition of The Manchester Guardian, now The Guardian, is published.[6]

events.description: The first railway in continental Europe opens between Brussels and Mechelen.
events.html: • 1835 – The first railway in continental Europe opens between Brussels and Mechelen.

entities.name: History of rail transport in Belgium

events.description: Cinco de Mayo: Troops led by Ignacio Zaragoza halt a French invasion in the Battle of Puebla in Mexico.
events.html: • 1862 – Cinco de Mayo: Troops led by Ignacio Zaragoza halt a French invasion in the Battle of Puebla in Mexico.

events.description: American Civil War: The Battle of the Wilderness begins in Spotsylvania County.
events.html: • 1864 – American Civil War: The Battle of the Wilderness begins in Spotsylvania County.

events.description: American Civil War: The Confederate government was declared dissolved at Washington, Georgia.
events.html: • 1865 – American Civil War: The Confederate government was declared dissolved at Washington, Georgia.

entities.name: Conclusion of the American Civil War

events.description: Memorial Day first celebrated in United States at Waterloo, New York.
events.html: • 1866 – Memorial Day first celebrated in United States at Waterloo, New York.

events.description: American Indian Wars: Sitting Bull leads his band of Lakota into Canada to avoid harassment by the United States Army under Colonel Nelson Miles.
events.html: • 1877 – American Indian Wars: Sitting Bull leads his band of Lakota into Canada to avoid harassment by the United States Army under Colonel Nelson Miles.

events.description: Workers marching for the Eight-hour day in Milwaukee, Wisconsin were shot at by Wisconsin National Guardsmen in what became known as the Bay View Massacre.
events.html: • 1886 – Workers marching for the Eight-hour day in Milwaukee, Wisconsin were shot at by Wisconsin National Guardsmen in what became known as the Bay View Massacre.[7]

events.description: The Peruvian Academy of Language is founded.
events.html: • 1887 – The Peruvian Academy of Language is founded.[8]

events.description: The Music Hall in New York City (later known as Carnegie Hall) has its grand opening and first public performance, with Tchaikovsky as the guest conductor.
events.html: • 1891 – The Music Hall in New York City (later known as Carnegie Hall) has its grand opening and first public performance, with Tchaikovsky as the guest conductor.

events.description: Pitching against the Philadelphia Athletics at the Huntington Avenue Grounds, Cy Young of the Boston Americans throws the first perfect game in the modern era of baseball.
events.html: • 1904 – Pitching against the Philadelphia Athletics at the Huntington Avenue Grounds, Cy Young of the Boston Americans throws the first perfect game in the modern era of baseball.

events.description: The trial in the Stratton Brothers case begins in London, England; it marks the first time that fingerprint evidence is used to gain a conviction for murder.
events.html: • 1905 – The trial in the Stratton Brothers case begins in London, England; it marks the first time that fingerprint evidence is used to gain a conviction for murder.

events.description: The first issue of the Bolshevik newspaper Pravda was published.
events.html: • 1912 – The first issue of the Bolshevik newspaper Pravda was published.[9]

events.description: Authorities arrest Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti for alleged robbery and murder.
events.html: • 1920 – Authorities arrest Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti for alleged robbery and murder.

events.description: The 1930 Bago earthquake, the former of two major earthquakes in southern Burma kills as many as 7,000 in Yangon and Bago.
events.html: • 1930 – The 1930 Bago earthquake, the former of two major earthquakes in southern Burma kills as many as 7,000 in Yangon and Bago.[10]

events.description: Italian troops occupy Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
events.html: • 1936 – Italian troops occupy Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.

events.description: World War II: Norwegian Campaign: Norwegian squads in Hegra Fortress and Vinjesvingen capitulate to German forces after all other Norwegian forces in southern Norway had laid down their arms.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: Norwegian Campaign: Norwegian squads in Hegra Fortress and Vinjesvingen capitulate to German forces after all other Norwegian forces in southern Norway had laid down their arms.

events.description: Emperor Haile Selassie returns to Addis Ababa; the country commemorates the date as Liberation Day or Patriots' Victory Day.
events.html: • 1941 – Emperor Haile Selassie returns to Addis Ababa; the country commemorates the date as Liberation Day or Patriots' Victory Day.

events.description: World War II: The Prague uprising begins as an attempt by the Czech resistance to free the city from German occupation.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: The Prague uprising begins as an attempt by the Czech resistance to free the city from German occupation.

events.description: World War II: A Fu-Go balloon bomb launched by the Japanese Army kills six people near Bly, Oregon.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: A Fu-Go balloon bomb launched by the Japanese Army kills six people near Bly, Oregon.

events.description: World War II: Battle of Castle Itter, one of only two battles in that war in which American and German troops fought cooperatively.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: Battle of Castle Itter, one of only two battles in that war in which American and German troops fought cooperatively.

events.description: The International Military Tribunal for the Far East begins in Tokyo with twenty-eight Japanese military and government officials accused of war crimes and crimes against humanity.
events.html: • 1946 – The International Military Tribunal for the Far East begins in Tokyo with twenty-eight Japanese military and government officials accused of war crimes and crimes against humanity.

entities.name: International Military Tribunal for the Far East

events.description: The General Treaty, by which France, Britain and the United States recognize the sovereignty of West Germany, comes into effect.
events.html: • 1955 – The General Treaty, by which France, Britain and the United States recognize the sovereignty of West Germany, comes into effect.

events.description: Project Mercury: Alan Shepard becomes the first American to travel into outer space, on a sub-orbital flight.
events.html: • 1961 – Project Mercury: Alan Shepard becomes the first American to travel into outer space, on a sub-orbital flight.

events.description: The Council of Europe declares May 5 as Europe Day.
events.html: • 1964 – The Council of Europe declares May 5 as Europe Day.

events.description: Alitalia Flight 112 crashes into Mount Longa near Palermo, Sicily, killing all 115 aboard, making it the deadliest single-aircraft disaster in Italy.
events.html: • 1972 – Alitalia Flight 112 crashes into Mount Longa near Palermo, Sicily, killing all 115 aboard, making it the deadliest single-aircraft disaster in Italy.

events.description: Secretariat wins the 1973 Kentucky Derby in 1:59.4, an as-yet-unbeaten record.
events.html: • 1973 – Secretariat wins the 1973 Kentucky Derby in 1:59.4, an as-yet-unbeaten record.

events.description: Operation Nimrod: The British Special Air Service storms the Iranian embassy in London after a six-day siege.
events.html: • 1980 – Operation Nimrod: The British Special Air Service storms the Iranian embassy in London after a six-day siege.

events.description: Bobby Sands dies in the Long Kesh prison hospital after 66 days of hunger-striking, aged 27.
events.html: • 1981 – Bobby Sands dies in the Long Kesh prison hospital after 66 days of hunger-striking, aged 27.

events.description: Ronald Reagan visits the military cemetery at Bitburg and the site of the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp, where he makes a speech.
events.html: • 1985 – Ronald Reagan visits the military cemetery at Bitburg and the site of the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp, where he makes a speech.

events.description: Iran–Contra affair: Start of Congressional televised hearings in the United States of America
events.html: • 1987 – Iran–Contra affair: Start of Congressional televised hearings in the United States of America

events.description: A riot breaks out in the Mt. Pleasant section of Washington, D.C. after police shoot a Salvadoran man.
events.html: • 1991 – A riot breaks out in the Mt. Pleasant section of Washington, D.C. after police shoot a Salvadoran man.

events.description: The signing of the Bishkek Protocol between Armenia and Azerbaijan effectively freezes the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict.
events.html: • 1994 – The signing of the Bishkek Protocol between Armenia and Azerbaijan effectively freezes the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict.

events.description: American teenager Michael P. Fay is caned in Singapore for theft and vandalism.
events.html: • 1994 – American teenager Michael P. Fay is caned in Singapore for theft and vandalism.

events.description: The government of Sudan signs an accord with the Sudan Liberation Army.
events.html: • 2006 – The government of Sudan signs an accord with the Sudan Liberation Army.[11]

events.description: Kenya Airways Flight 507 crashes after takeoff from Douala International Airport in Douala, Cameroon, killing all 114 aboard, making it the deadliest aircraft disaster in Cameroon.
events.html: • 2007 – Kenya Airways Flight 507 crashes after takeoff from Douala International Airport in Douala, Cameroon, killing all 114 aboard, making it the deadliest aircraft disaster in Cameroon.[12]

events.html: • 2010 – Mass protests in Greece erupt in response to austerity measures imposed by the government as a result of the Greek government-debt crisis.

events.description: The World Health Organization declares the end of the COVID-19 pandemic as a global health emergency.
events.html: • 2023 – The World Health Organization declares the end of the COVID-19 pandemic as a global health emergency.[13]
